"""
    Filling missing county, city and ZIP based on address_line_1
    Author: Bhavana
"""
# Filter rows in the properties_df DataFrame where first we decided to fill missing data for 'City', 'County', and 'ZIP' columns
rows_to_geocode = properties_df[pd.isna(properties_df['City']) | pd.isna(properties_df['County']) | pd.isna(properties_df['ZIP'])]

# Instantiate a Photon geolocator
geolocator = Photon(user_agent="measurements")

# Use rate limiter to manage request frequency and avoiding API limits
geocode = RateLimiter(geolocator.geocode, min_delay_seconds=1, error_wait_seconds=10)

# Function to fill missing City, County and ZIP based on Address_Line_1 column
def fill_geo_details(row):
    try:
        # Geocode the address by using Address_Line_1 column
        location = geocode(row['Address_Line_1'])
        if location:
            address = location.raw['properties']
            # If 'City' is missing and found in the geocoded result, then fill it with that value
            if pd.isna(row['City']) and 'city' in address:
                row['City'] = address['city']
            # If 'County' is missing and found in the geocoded result, then fill it with that value
            if pd.isna(row['County']) and 'county' in address:
                row['County'] = address['county']
            # If 'ZIP' is missing and found in the geocoded result, then fill it with that value
            if pd.isna(row['ZIP']) and 'postcode' in address:
                row['ZIP'] = address['postcode']
    except (GeocoderTimedOut, GeocoderServiceError) as e:
        print(f"Geocoding service error: {e}. Skipping {row['Address_Line_1']}.")
    # Handling exceptions
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error geocoding {row['Address_Line_1']}: {e}")
    return row

# Iterate over each row and update the dataframe
for index, row in tqdm(rows_to_geocode.iterrows(), total=rows_to_geocode.shape[0]):
    properties_df.loc[index] = fill_geo_details(row)

"""
    Filling missing Latitude and Longitude based on raw files in which US ZIP, Latitude and Longitude are present
    Author: Bhavana
"""
# Loading the dataframe which contains the zip code latitude and longitude data given as reference
zip_lat_lng_df = pd.read_csv('https://gist.githubusercontent.com/erichurst/7882666/raw/5bdc46db47d9515269ab12ed6fb2850377fd869e/US%2520Zip%2520Codes%2520from%25202013%2520Government%2520Data')

# Converting ZIP column to string data type
zip_lat_lng_df['ZIP'] = zip_lat_lng_df['ZIP'].astype(str)

# Merge the latitude and longitude data with properties_df on ZIP code
# Apply 'left' join which means that all rows from properties_df will be included in the resulting DataFrame, along with matching rows from zip_lat_lng_df based on the 'ZIP' code. 

properties_df = properties_df.merge(zip_lat_lng_df, on='ZIP', how='left')

# In case where there is no direct match, the code then imputes values based on averages within the same city and county for filling latitude and longitude.
properties_df['Latitude'].fillna(properties_df.groupby(['City', 'County'])['Latitude'].transform('mean'), inplace=True)
properties_df['Longitude'].fillna(properties_df.groupby(['City', 'County'])['Longitude'].transform('mean'), inplace=True)

# Display the count of missing values
missing_values_after_imputation = properties_df[['Latitude', 'Longitude']].isna().sum()
print("Missing Latitude and Longitude Values After Imputation:")
print(missing_values_after_imputation)

"""
    Filling remaining Latitude and Longitude data which was not present in raw file by using geolocator
    Author: Bhavana
"""
# Creating a geolocator object using Photon along with a specific user-agent named measurements
geolocator = Photon(user_agent="measurements")

# Function to fill missing latitude and longitude values using the geolocator
def fill_missing_coordinates(row):
    try:
        # Finding the address using Photon geolocator
        location = geolocator.geocode(f"{row['Address_Line_1']}, {row['City']}, {row['County']}, {row['ZIP']}")
        if location:
            row['Latitude'] = location.latitude
            row['Longitude'] = location.longitude
    except (GeocoderTimedOut, GeocoderServiceError) as e:
        print(f"Geocoding service error: {e}. Skipping {row['Address_Line_1']}.")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error geocoding {row['Address_Line_1']}: {e}")
    return row

# Running the geolocator only on missing latitude and longitude values for streamlining the process 
missing_lat_lng = properties_df[pd.isna(properties_df['Latitude']) | pd.isna(properties_df['Longitude'])]

# Applying the function to fill missing values
filled_missing_lat_lng = missing_lat_lng.apply(fill_missing_coordinates, axis=1)
properties_df.update(filled_missing_lat_lng)

# Drop rows with missing values in the 'Latitude', 'Longitude' columns because they are mostly road, lanes which is not having specific latitude and longitude
properties_df.dropna(subset=['Latitude', 'Longitude'], inplace=True)

In [13]:
"""
    Filled missing Sale Price by removing extreme outliers
    Author: Bhavana
"""
# Calculate IQR(i.e Q1 and Q3) for 'Sale Price'
Q1_sale = properties_df['Sale Price'].quantile(0.25)
Q3_sale = properties_df['Sale Price'].quantile(0.75)
IQR_sale = Q3_sale - Q1_sale
median_sale = properties_df['Sale Price'].median()

# Filtering extreme outliers based on Interquartile Range method
properties_df['Sale Price'] = properties_df['Sale Price'].apply(
    lambda x: median_sale if x < Q1_sale - 1.5 * IQR_sale or x > Q3_sale + 1.5 * IQR_sale else x)

"""
    Replacing missing Sale Price with median based on Property Type
    Author: Bhavana
"""
# Calculate median Sale Price values for each Property Type after removing outliers
imputation_values_sale = properties_df.groupby('Property Type')['Sale Price'].median()

# Fill missing Sale Price values based on Property Type : Imputation Created
def fill_missing_sale_price(row):
    if pd.isna(row['Sale Price']):
        property_type = row['Property Type']
        row['Sale Price'] = imputation_values_sale[property_type]
    return row

# Imputation applied for filling missing Sale Price values
properties_df = properties_df.apply(fill_missing_sale_price, axis=1)

# Aggregation applied for each column
agg_methods = {
    'Market Value': 'mean',        # Average of the Market Value
    'Sale Price': 'max',           # Maximum of the Sale Price
    'Property Type': 'first',      # First value of Property Type
    'Latitude': 'first',           # First value of Latitude
    'Longitude': 'first',          # First value of Longitude
    'Coverage_Building %': 'first',# First value of Coverage Building %
    'Coverage_Contents %': 'first',# First value of Coverage Contents %
    'Coverage_Outbuildings %': 'first' # First value of Coverage Outbuildings %
}

# Grouping by address('Address_Line_1', 'City', 'ZIP', 'County') and then apply the above aggregation
properties_df = properties_df.groupby(['Address_Line_1', 'City', 'ZIP', 'County']).agg(agg_methods).reset_index()

    Author: Bhavana, Tabassum, Deepika, Patrick

    properties_df,

)

"""
    Filter the properties based on Single Family Residence and Condominiums along with Impacted area greater than 60%
    Author: Bhavana
"""
def extract_upper_bound(percentage_str):
    if pd.isna(percentage_str):
        return None  
    # Remove the percent sign before conversion
    percentage_str = percentage_str.replace('%', '')
    # Handling cases like '<5'
    if percentage_str.startswith('<'):
        return 0.0
    # Handling cases like '>90'
    elif percentage_str.startswith('>'):
        return float(percentage_str[1:])
    # Handling ranges like '30-40'/'50-60' and many more
    elif '-' in percentage_str:
        return float(percentage_str.split('-')[1])
    else:
        return float(percentage_str)

# Applying the function to create a new column 'Impact Upper Bound'for storing the Percentage Bounded values
joined_gdf['Impact Upper Bound'] = joined_gdf['PERCENTAGE'].apply(extract_upper_bound)

# Filter the GeoDataFrame for properties with more than 60% impact probability
# and Property Type code 167 or 45 (i.e Single Family Residence and Condominiums)
filtered_properties = joined_gdf[
    (joined_gdf['Property Type'].isin(["Single Family Residence", "Condominiums"])) &
    (joined_gdf['Impact Upper Bound'] > 60)
]

# Verifying the filtered properties by printing
filtered_properties[['Address_Line_1', 'City', 'ZIP', 'County', 'Sale Price', 'Market Value', 'Latitude', 'Longitude', 'Property Type', 'Coverage_Building %', 'Coverage_Contents %', 'Coverage_Outbuildings %', 'PERCENTAGE']]

Determine Coverages¶

In [31]:
"""
    Determining the Coverages along with Total Exposure
    Author: Bhavana, Tabassum, Deepika, Patrick
"""
# Building Coverage Calculation
properties_data['Building Coverage'] = properties_data['Property Value'] * (properties_data['Coverage_Building %'] / 100.0)

# Contents Coverage Calculation
properties_data['Contents Coverage'] = properties_data['Building Coverage'] * (properties_data['Coverage_Contents %'] / 100.0)

# Outbuilding Coverage Calculation
properties_data['Outbuildings Coverage'] = properties_data['Building Coverage'] * (properties_data['Coverage_Outbuildings %'] / 100.0)

# Total Exposure Calculation
properties_data['Total Exposure'] = properties_data['Building Coverage'] + properties_data['Contents Coverage'] + properties_data['Outbuildings Coverage']

# Display the records with new coverage columns


[['Address_Line_1', 'City', 'ZIP', 'County', 'Property Value', 'Building Coverage', 'Contents Coverage', 'Outbuildings Coverage', 'Total Exposure']]

Step 7 - Visualization¶

In [38]:
"""
    Map to show top 5 ZIP codes with number of affected properties 
    Author: Bhavana
"""
# Create a base map focused on Florida Map latitude and longitude values
m = folium.Map(location=[27.9944024, -81.7602544], zoom_start=7)
# Added a full-screen button to the map
Fullscreen(position='topright', title='Expand me', title_cancel='Exit me', force_separate_button=True).add_to(m)

class TooltipStyle(MacroElement):
    _template = Template("""
        {% macro header(this, kwargs) %}
            <style>
                .leaflet-tooltip {
                    font-size: 18px !important;
                    font-weight: bold !important;
                }
            </style>
        {% endmacro %}
        """) 
    

# Added a markers
marker_cluster = MarkerCluster().add_to(m)
cyclone_icon_url = 'https://www.freeiconspng.com/thumbs/hurricane-icon/hurricane-graphic-14.png'

# CSS to increase tooltip size
class BindColoredIcon(MacroElement):
    def __init__(self):
        super(BindColoredIcon, self).__init__()
        self._template = Template("""
            {% macro script(this, kwargs) %}
            document.styleSheets[0].insertRule('.leaflet-tooltip-top:before, .leaflet-tooltip-left:before, .leaflet-tooltip-right:before, .leaflet-tooltip-bottom:before { border-top-color: transparent !important;}', 0);
            document.styleSheets[0].insertRule('.leaflet-tooltip.leaflet-zoom-animated { font-size: 18px; }', 0);
            {% endmacro %}
            """)

m.get_root().add_child(BindColoredIcon())

# Add top 5 highly affected ZIP codes
for zip_code, count in top_5_affected_count.items():
    properties_in_zip = filtered_properties[filtered_properties['ZIP'] == zip_code]
    avg_lat = properties_in_zip['Latitude'].mean()
    avg_lon = properties_in_zip['Longitude'].mean()
    
    # Display the most common county and city within the ZIP code
    most_common_county = properties_in_zip['County'].mode()[0]
    most_common_city = properties_in_zip['City'].mode()[0]

    # HTML popup for font size
    popup_html = f"<div style='font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;'>ZIP Code: {zip_code}<br>Number of Affected Properties: {count}</div>"
    iframe = IFrame(html=popup_html, width=200, height=100)
    popup = folium.Popup(iframe, max_width=2650)
    
    # Tooltip text
    tooltip = folium.Tooltip(f"{most_common_city}, {most_common_county}", style="font-size: 18px;")

    # Custom icon
    cyclone_icon = CustomIcon(
        icon_image=cyclone_icon_url,
        icon_size=(30, 30)
    )

    folium.Marker(
        location=[avg_lat, avg_lon],
        popup=popup,
        tooltip=tooltip,
        icon=cyclone_icon
    ).add_to(marker_cluster)

# Display the map
m.get_root().add_child(TooltipStyle())
